<review>A completely amazing experience! I'm not sure where to even begin, but I wish I could give them 15 stars for customer service and the overall experience.
- Ease of renting. 5‚≠ê 's. We decided late Saturday night to rent a Harley on Sunday. - In store experience 5+5‚≠ê's.  I wish I could name everyone in this store because they're all awesome! Down to earth, happy, helpful, bike loving people.  Brandon and Ryan are the reason we had such a great day.  Brandon handled the rental, did the service check, walked me through the bike from wheel to wheel, broke out a map and we talked through the route and what would enhance the ride, and got us out the door. He also checked us back in and we talked about the different styles HD is carrying as a comparison for what we rode   Ryan walked with us around the shop, pulled up maps on his phone, and made some suggestions to the route to make sure we had the most scenic ride possible. - The bike. 5 ‚≠ê's.  We rented a Street Glide Grand Touring bike. It really doesn't get much better.  It handled like a luxury performance vehicle, no surprise it's Harley Davidson! Lots of storage space, comfortable seats, my better half was in heaven on the back seat.

< review>
While visiting from Germany my friend got a day off to have me ride with him in SD county. So I headed to Eagle Rider yesterday evening. I wasn't sure if the trip was gonna happen and a little bit tired after spending all day in LA. So Anitra told me to not sweat it if I'm tired and not 100% sure and come back in the morning. We wanted to start the tour at 9 and Eagle Rider didn't open until 10. However, Anitra told me that she would come in a little earlier to get me on the road. This morning I headed to Eagle Rider after my buddy confirmed and Anitra was there to attend me. She walked me through the process of the rental and took my data, German driver license and my card for payment. Made sure I knew everything I needed about the bike, some routes, and the return. We spend a wonderful day in SD county. I even got a new 2018 Fatboy, the bike I'm actually looking to buy. The bike was impeccable, the ride smooth. Came back at 6:40 PM 20 minutes before closing with a full tank of gas. Anitra was there for the return, as promised. She showed genuine interest in my experience and was very kind and professional. The next time I'm in town I will definitely come back here. Highly recommend!< /review>

This was a great experience. People were helpful. I contact the shop before renting to have info about Supplemental Liability Insurance and they were happy to help. My only feed-back is to consider to allow returning the bike later than 4pm. 4 pm fells a bit too "in the middle of the day".

<rating>4</rating>< Review>
(Translated by Google) As part of our self-planned tour of the Western United States, we quickly decided to rent a Harley on August 3rd, 2014 at EagleRider. Unlike the hustle and bustle of Eagle Rider in Los Angeles and the long wait for pickup due to heavy traffic, I can only recommend EagleRider San Diego as an absolute insider tip. Nice welcome, very personal and friendly, our booked Harley Street Glide was unavailable due to a previous total loss. We were offered 2 similar machines, we chose an Indian Chieftain, and it was a good decision. New machine, top condition, easy handling. The return was completely relaxed. Super. We will be back.

(Original)
Wir haben uns im Rahmen unserer selbst geplanten Tour durch den Westen der USA kurzfristig dazu entschieden am 03.August 2014 bei EagleRider eine Harleyauszuleihen. <user_id>108442501673428661778< /user_id>< review>
Dollar Tree is consistently a good place to shop for every day items as well as seasonal items and greeting cards. Cleaning supplies and laundry detergent are available as well as dishware and kitchen accessories. They also have some health and beauty products, toys, craft items, and pet supplies. They carry canned goods, candy, snacks, and some beverages.  Shelf stable milk and almond milk are often available. There is even a frozen grocery item section that is stocked with a variety of food items. Dollar Tree's generic brands often have the identical ingredients to name brands for a fraction of the cost. Some of my favorite products there for value is their mouthwash that is comparable to Listerine as well as their soaps and first aid creams.< /review>

<Text>Very cute restaurant. And really really good food!!
We came here on a Wed evening. Lots of place available. Got seated at a booth, which was lovely. We ordered the Tom kar chicken soup, the poh tak seafood soup, red curry with white rice and drunken noodles.

The soup was beautiful. They added spicy chilli and peppers which was nice touch. The seafood soup was also very good. My brother took the whole lot to himself as his meal and still couldn't finish it. I tried the broth of it and it was pretty tasty. My parents LOVED the red curry. They ordered a spice level 3/10 and thought it was spicy enough for them. My drunken noodles were really tasty. I ordered a spice level of 7/10 and it was appropriately spicy for me. We also got a Thai tea which my dad said was good.

Overall, great experience and will be back for more!!< /Text><Name>Pranjali Sharma</Name>< date>
1571966180856<//date>

<username>Mohit Bhushan</username>< Text>
I came across Swaddee by chance while walking the streets around Hotel Del.  The restaurant decor is real nice, representative of Thai art and foliage.  The servers are dressed in traditional garb and friendly.  Bathrooms are super clean, a big plus.  Prices are very reasonable and service very good.  The menu is pretty much what ever Thai restaurant offers - salads, soups, starters and entrees ranging from stir fry dishes to curries with one's choice of meat or tofu.  Food was just delicious.  It was freshly prepared and the spice level was optimized to our unique palettes.  Will visit again when in Coronado.  If you feel the urge to cool off after the Thai meal, walk right next door to Nado Gelato, another great hangout place.<//Text>

<Text>We've been coming here for about 5 years now and LOVE it. I noticed other reviews that said the service was poor however we've never had a bad experience. I always get the Gang Kua with just veggies, no meat or tofu with a side of sticky rice. Never fails to hit the spot. I've also tried the vegetarian spring rolls and the dumplings. Both were great. Friends that we go with always try different things and are never disappointed. WARNING: If they tell you it's spicy they mean it! I can usually hold my own but the one time I tried a different dish that was spicy the lady told me I probably wouldn't like it. She was right and I thought I was dying.  It is a bit on the pricier end. Expect to pay about $40 for dinner for 2 (drinks, appetizer and meals) but it's worth it to me based on the food, atmosphere and considering it's on Coronado. The restaurants there tend to be a bit more than I would spend elsewhere anyway.<//Text><Pics>None</Pics><response>None< /response><Gmap_id>0x80deaccbff945b77:0x3e25c0c9d0c9d2fa<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<rating>5<//rating><Review>We spent a week in San Diego sampling restaurants and touring the city.  By weeks end alll four of us agreed that the Swaddee Thai Restaurant was one of our top finds.  We loved the bright decor and the staffs traditional dress.  The service was very polite and accommodating.  The food was the star of the evening.  Our son and his wife had the vegetarian spring rolls which were slightly overcooked but delicious.  The accompanying pork dumplings were some of the best we've ever had.  Each dumpling was moist with ground pork and an understated sauce making for 2-3 bites each.  The red curry, coconut with chicken, bamboo, eggplant etc was slightly spicy and perfectly prepared.  I immensely enjoyed the pad thai which I ordered with tender shrimp and was served with a healthy topping of ground peanut for added texture.  The bill was quite reasonable and a real bargain for the experience.  Wish this restaurant was in our hometown!<//Review><pictures>None</pictures><response>None</response>< Gmap_id>

< userid>
109815267831202318650< /userid>
< Name>
Walter Macalma<//Name>
< Time>
1448232168072< /Time>
<Rate>5< /Rate><text>The good thing about Thai food, is now I know how it's all made and I'm a much better judge of things since I took a Thai cooking class. My first experience of Thai since that class and I really tried to use my palate to sense the subtle variances in each restaurant. First of all d√©cor is light, simple, clean and neat. They use white table clothes and serve on porcelain dishes. Each table has fresh flowers on it that really let you know they care. The pricing is very competitive, unlike many places on the island that are not with similar establishments off the island. Not a bad place to take a date as there is plenty to walk around and do afterwards in the area, gelato shop called Moo something is my suggestion.

Tom Ka soup seemed to be more clear than expected, but just the right amount of sour from the tamarind. I prefer the rounded out taste of black/white pepper to some people who add hot pepper to their soups. I also prefer the minimal bamboo shoots, which as many know if not cooked/soaked properly can be little daggers.

Pad Si Eew had tender beef and succulent broccoli, but I found the noodles to be a a little broken and the sauce to be a tad burned, which is weird because I found the soy they used to be saltier than most sweet soy's and I'd imagine the burning was from the sugars. Nice size for 1 person, but I've got a healthy appetite and I went with the Green Curry which was thick and hearty, needed very little rice to compliment it. I went with the 5 spice level and it was tame, I prefer a measured scale rather than the exponential type which I feel is meant to deter people from over spicing, but hard for us who like and can handle spice to accurately judge.

As good as a thai iced tea is the real business is in the coffee. Yes I understand the price can be off putting, but it's really not pricey for the quality you get and it's been so engrained in us that Asian food is usually cheap. The average person can't appreciate the scale of good to bad and fine dining isn't exclusive to Italian and French and things you can't cook. We're so accustomed to getting $6 pad thai in a slightly large portion, but doesn't taste homecooked. So when you see a restaurant serving high quality Thai food in a better than average setting you seem blown away at paying $15 for that. You could go to outback and get a mediocre steak for the same price and not skip a beat, but proportionally bad is that compared to Ruth's Chris or Mortons.< /text><pics>None</pics>< Resp>
None<//Resp>

<Name>Esra K< /Name><Date>1482619089177< /Date>< Rating>
1</Rating>
< text>
Serving San Diego with honesty and integrity since 1989 is what their website announces! My experience here certainly did not meet that slogan they have.

If you need used tires, there are some good shops around. Especially the place next to this place is amazing (see reviews by searching tires shops on the maps).

Coming to the reasoning behind the 1 star is that this place almost locked me up in their small office while overcharging me as part of dishonest business practices. I was quoted $70.00 (over the phone) for 2 used (but still intact) tires. One I walked in, the price was suddenly $80.00 out the door for two used tires. Pretty good deal you would say until I had to pay..:

Once they sticked my card into the chip reader in a cramped( office?) room, the guy suddenly pushed in 3 digits in instead of 2; that's where I noticed that something did not seem quit right.

My guts were right as the guy was nonchalantly charging me  w/o the heads up an additional $20.00  for removing the locks?
-WOW-
It would've been ok if they told me that they would charge another $20.00 for doing that, but no communication about extra charge whatsoever. "Are these prices posted anywhere? "Not that I have seen..

I strongly got the feeling that they were trying to overcharge me just for being "foreign" (from Europe) to them instead of a Hispanic person (which were just like the shop owners as well as the patrons present). I think they shouldn't pull such strings on people out of the blue and think that we won't care.

Will not come back, as they stole my money without informing priorly.  management practice. Most workers here are really friendly however and they are just doing their job.

Furthermore, There is no seating or specific waiting area as well, so it made our whole experience a bit awkward by blocking constantly the worker's way in the rain-ish weather.

Oh well, next time the place next door. These guy simply will rip you off! The  neighborhood is a rough one as well so imagine standing there on almost the sidewalk.....< /text>

< user>

<rate>4</rate>< review>
Pleasant space with friendly bartenders.  I only have two real complaints, both relating to the fact that it's very hard to socialize with friends.   1. The seating inside is at at least 4 different heights....super low sofas, high stools, low stools, medium chairs... all different.  You wind up talking to someone's belly button, or they into your knees.   2. The audio from the pianists (which are quite good, btw) tends to be over amplified - usually  much louder in the front of the bar than right at the piano.   I would suggest more present at the piano where people want to listen 100%  and more background in the front and outside where folks want to be more social.  All that said, it's nice to have a real piano bar back in the neighborhood.</review>

< Text>
I was having a rough morning, until I went to Bymar. I began the morning trying to get one tire changed at a Just Tires in Irvine off of Jamboree. They left me standing out there past the opening time, even though we made eye contact, and I just had to wait there patiently. Once they finally opened the door, they were extremely rude and short with me when trying to buy a replacement tire. As a female, I often have a bad experience when it comes to anything automotive so I wasn‚Äôt surprise. I left there feeling insulted and low, which is when I decided would never return there.

I had my husband call around to find a place closer to home, and he found Bymar. The experience was night and day; they were welcoming, kind, did not keep me waiting, showed me the tire they were replacing and why, and the pricing was fair. Moving forward, this will be my go to for tires and I will recommend them to others as well. They were professional and the tire feels great while driving.

On a side note, their bathroom was extremely clean and they also offered fresh coffee for customers. Thumbs up for Bymar!<//Text>

< Review>
Horrible business practices. I checked in at 9am for a 10 am appointment. Showed up at 950am, to be early, let them know my name and after they verified I had an appointment I sat down. It was busy with 2 families and multiple kids.

At about 958am a lady walks in with 3 kids. Proceeds to the front and talks to, whom I can only assume is, the manager.
She tells her some sob story about her poor time management skills and next thing I know is one of her kids being ushered into one of the chairs. So I was like "ok one kid cutting is not too bad" as there were a total of 4 hair dressers in. Then when the other hair stylists were finishing up the mom was told that her other kids can go sit.
So I ask politely what is going on, that I had an appointment at 10am and it's already 1015. I was informed that I would be seen after they were all done and taken care of.
Finally after forever of the kids and their mom getting a hair cut there is a spot open.

So I stand up, because my appointment was past due, and at that moment some young guy comes in. The lady that was free apparently knows him as he goes straight to her and then she leads him to the chair and starts to prep him.
I was appalled and began checking the appointment times of other hair cutting places. Unfortunately their next available appointment was not for another 30 minutes so I stayed as surely I was next. One of the other hair stylist was done and told me it was now my turn.

I informed the lady what stye I wanted and just sat quietly in my chair while she did my hair.
When the hair cut was done and I was paying I let her know what was on my mind. I told her that they had a horrible business practice. I told her "piss poor planning on someone else's part doesn't equal to me getting delayed. Just because someone else can't properly manage their time doesn't mean my time should get messed up".

Time is money and mine got robbed. I will never again be a client at a location where they don't respect a client's appointment.  If you have an appointment then it should be honored. Or, at the very least, asked if it is fine that they take care of someone else. They just assumed I would be fine with being screwed over. I was not fine at all.

If you know a hair stylist or suck at managing time then this place is perfect for you. However, if you have places to be and other appointments to attend to then stay clear of this location. They don't respect your time, they don't respect your appointment.

As such I am taking my business elsewhere to a place that will respect my time.< /Review>

<review>I had a shockingly bad experience trying to work with this dealership. It really defined my understanding of "bad business".

I've condensed this story best I could. I was an out-of-state buyer. I couldn't physically be at the dealership, so I was going to buy/finance remotely and then fly over and drive the car home. Over the span of 5 days, I expressed constant interest in a very recently posted car, and was ready to buy the car immediately for the full listed price + whatever fees as soon as pictures were posted (as It was suggested I should wait). Genuinely it was the car and deal I had been looking for a few months, and the salesman I worked with knew that. The night before the big day, I was told by the current salesman on my case, Christian, that he'd reach out the second he located the car and could get pictures to me. The next day, I check the website at noon, and magically the car's pictures had been posted to the website, and it was on the showroom floor. Frantically I call and tell Christian we want go forward with buying the car and we are getting the financials in order and we need an hour. Christian calls shortly later and says the manager is okay holding the car for an hour, and at that point in time I tell him we are completely ready to go. He tells me he will send the payment information as soon as he hangs up. 30 minutes go by, no email, he calls, and tells me a customer has just arrived and is asking about it. This is when everything seems to be thrown out the window. The car is suddenly not being held, and their magical "first come first serve" policy only seems to apply to the customer that just walked in, not the customer that is outright trying to buy the car at that very moment, and has been communicating constant interest over the last 5 days.

Christian hangs up shortly after, and then completely ghosts. I call multiple times. I talk to other salesman, one even catches Christian walking by and tells him to call me. Nothing. 5 hours and multiple calls later, I am told by another salesman the car has just been sold. Christian never reached out.

Maybe out-of-state is a little bit harder to work with, but the lack of integrity shown was shocking. Not only did they entirely disregard a weeks worth of continued strong interest and commitment to pay immediately when it was ready, but the complete ghosting that followed was incredibly unprofessional. It is important to note that Christian was only one of a good handful of people that knew I was interested and prepared to buy the car as soon as it was properly documented.

I'd wager if your an in-person buyer you won't face this issue directly, but it is important to understand the underlying integrity of a few people you might end up working with. I want to add that the first salesman I worked with, Guy Peterson, did a great job and proved that his own commission was clearly not the first priority.<//review>< pictures>

He explained everything to me up front before I could even ask any questions and made sure that he would do his best to have my car serviced within the time-frame that I asked for.

I came back about a half-hour before the time promised and hung out in the waiting area. Vince walked by, noticed me right away and let me know that my car was being washed and would be ready shortly. Once my car was ready and waiting, Vince called me out, shook my hand and assured me that my car was good to go.

I really felt like I was in good hands with Vince. He will definitely be my service go to
guy in the future.</Text>

< review>
I had visited several other Audi dealerships in the SoCal area and I had a pretty good understanding of what I wanted. Audi Rusnak was hands down the best Audi dealership that I visited. Yalonda Conrad was my sales rep and she did an amazing job. For several weeks, I discussed the price of a particular vehicle with her online. She offered me a very competitive deal on this car. Unfortunately, someone else pulled the trigger on it before I could.

Not only was Audi Rusnak able to trade the other dealership for this car, they gave me a very comparable price to the original one I wanted even though this one had a higher MSRP. Yalonda, and her manager, Joe Najar, were very friendly and treated me with the utmost respect throughout this process. I never felt pressured into doing anything. < Text>
We purchased a Q5 with Rick at Rusnak Pasadena in September 2015. We have to say Rick is great, helpful and knowledgeable. He followed up several time after we made the purchase and our communication has always been efficient and effective. This review is not about our experience with Rick.

The awful nightmare started with Kevin Khourjian, the finance manager at this dealership. First, we were lured into the Audi Term Care Select package during the purchase, and he promised that we could cancel it in a month and get full refund. So we did some studies afterward and decided to cancel this package. This was still within the one-month period he promised, and we never used any of the service from the package. We called Kevin on Oct 12, 2015, faxed and emailed him the form and a written notice. First, I have to say he was very impatient over the phone. Since I understand the psychology here, I didn‚Äôt make it a big deal. On the phone, we were told explicitly that the service package was cancelled, but he had no written confirmation to show us. All we could to do was to wait and the refund would appear on the loan principle. So we waited for 3 months, but nothing happened‚Ä¶

On Jan 2, 2016 we took the car to this dealership for maintenance and got a chance to talk to Kevin in person. The moment I walked into his office, I saw my faxed paperwork sitting on top of his cabinet. I asked him about the case progress, he replied, ‚Äúoh some documents got lost and that paperwork was never processed.‚Äù Seriously? So why were we told the cancellation was done three months ago in the beginning? Even if ‚Äúsome documents‚Äù were lost, he had three months to call us or emailed us about that, but he did NOTHING.

After the struggling conversation, Kevin said he would process the paperwork again. We asked for his business card and left the dealership hoping this is the last time we spend time on it. But to be honest, we can hardly trust what he SAYs anymore, even if he called us right after we left the dealership to confirm that he has taken action. So we waited for another FIVE weeks, and we were right, NOTHING happened. I called his office three times, left voice messages, never heard back from him.

We used to have great trust in our dealership, at least expecting people to deal with things in a professional manner. We thought AUDI represents not only a standard for high-end driving experience, but also its superior customer service. Unfortunately, it is clearly NOT the case at this dealership, if not the opposite. I think this dealership pays great attention on getting new customers, but once you are in, what so called ‚ÄúSERVICE‚Äù becomes a big joke. < review>
I needed professional help. After 8 years living in London without any need for a car, I was moving back to the US and needed to get a new car. Before arrival, I did my research and was reasonably certain I wanted an Audi S5 Sportback. But I certainly wouldn't buy it without driving it. I'll be living in Pasadena, so wanted to go to the local dealer, which is Rusnak. I got in touch with Ricardo Torres a few weeks before moving back to Pasadena, and he was brilliant in helping explain leasing options and getting us preapproved while we were still in the UK. One day after we arrived in LA, I was test driving a few Audi models for comparisons. Ricardo Torres was great at getting us acquainted with the new cars and new technologies. The performance of the S5 convinced me it was indeed the right car for me. Ricardo helped us stay calm and collected throughout the leasing process. He was always there to answer any of our questions, was knowledgeable about the S5, and helped us navigate our choices. The financing process was also very smooth. And when we picked up the car, we had an excellent technology lesson from Matthew Dowley to help us understand the tech aspects. Working with Ricardo Torres was a real pleasure. After nearly 10 years without even needing a car, I needed to be brought into the 21st century, and we couldn't be happier with our new S5 or with the excellent customer service from Rusnak. I would definitely recommend Ricardo Torres if you are looking for a great guide.<//review>

They don't have the power to put it in so Jason(miserable human in general) comes over and says he doesn't remember telling me this.
